What is the ML ?

- Some Quotes about Machine Learning

 
“ Give a computer the ability to learn without being explicitly programmed.

— Athur Samuel (1901-1990)

  well proposed learning problem :

“A computer program is said to learn from experience E with respect to some task T and some performance measure P, if its performance on T, as measured by P, improves with experience E.

— Tom Mitchell (1951-present)

The Concept

Machine Learning is a Method for teaching computer to make and improve predictions or behaviors based on the data.

For me, ML is somewhat similar to statistical inference.

                           new data

input data -> Machine (Learn) –> Model (parameter Optimization) –>

Some basics and terms

  • vector : 1-Dimensional array. normally expressed as \(K=\{a,b,c,d\}\)

  • n : number of observation.

  • p : number of variables that are available for use in making predictions. e.g) year,age,sex, and more..

  • $ x_{i,j} $ is element of an X matrix, representing the value of the jth variable for the ith observation, where i = 1, 2,…,n and j = 1, 2,…,p.

\[ X = \left( \begin{array} {rrrr} x_{11} & x_{12} & \cdots & x_{1p} \\ x_{21} & x_{22} & \cdots & x_{2p} \\ \vdots & \vdots & \ddots & \vdots \\ x_{n1} & \cdots & \cdots & x_{np} \\ \end{array} \right) \]

Statistical Inference and ML.

| ML | Statistical Inference | DATA -> sampled data -> inference -> DATA

k-Nearleast Neighbor (k-NN)

  • Most simplest alogrithm which find k samples ~~ majority of vote.

\[ Dist_{(p,q)} = \sqrt{\sum_{x=1}^{n}{(p_{x}-q_{x})^2}} \]

  • n dimensions

\[ Dist_{(p,q)} = \sqrt{\sum_{x=1}^{n}{(p_{1}-q_{1})^2 + (p_{2}-q_{2})^2 + (p_{3}-q_{3})^2 ... (p_{n}-q_{n})^2}} \]

   iris_dist<-dist(iris[,1:3],upper=T,diag=T)     ## calculate euclidean distance
   iris_dist<-as.data.frame(as.matrix(iris_dist)) ## change dist object -> matrix -> data.frame
   
   iris_dist[1:5,1:5]

   iris_mds_df<-as.data.frame(mds_iris$`points`)
